00:25:38,460 --> 00:25:40,020
because it's not supposed to be a seminar,

503
00:25:40,020 --> 00:25:42,660
but at the same time, if I just stand here and wave my arms around

504
00:25:42,660 --> 00:25:45,260
and say, yeah, take it from me, it's really going to happen,

505
00:25:45,260 --> 00:25:46,780
you really should not believe me.

506
00:25:46,780 --> 00:25:49,260
So I'm going to show you that we can do some experiments,

507
00:25:49,260 --> 00:25:51,980
that this is actually science,

508
00:25:51,980 --> 00:25:54,860
and I'll show you the kind of experiments that we can do.

509
00:25:54,860 --> 00:25:56,660
I'm going to skim over them quite lightly,

510
00:25:56,660 --> 00:25:59,380
and if you've got questions, feel free to either interrupt

511
00:25:59,380 --> 00:26:03,500
and ask as I'm going along, or ask at the end.

512
00:26:03,500 --> 00:26:08,220
Anyway, so this idea that life is powered by electric membranes,

513
00:26:08,220 --> 00:26:11,820
it goes back to 1961,

514
00:26:11,820 --> 00:26:15,180
to a paper from Peter Mitchell in 1961

515
00:26:15,180 --> 00:26:17,980
on what he called the chemiosmotic hypothesis,

516
00:26:17,980 --> 00:26:21,380
and this is an older picture, and it's with Jennifer Moyle,

517
00:26:21,380 --> 00:26:27,020
and Jennifer Moyle, she was working with Mitchell from 1947,

518
00:26:27,020 --> 00:26:29,260
this is 1947 in Cambridge,

519
00:26:29,260 --> 00:26:32,380
and she was a brilliant experimentalist,

520
00:26:32,380 --> 00:26:36,060
and most of the good papers that they wrote together in the 1960s

521
00:26:36,060 --> 00:26:37,380
on the chemiosmotic hypothesis

522
00:26:37,460 --> 00:26:40,100
is the best papers were Mitchell and Moyle together,

523
00:26:40,100 --> 00:26:42,700
and she did all the experimental work.

524
00:26:42,700 --> 00:26:44,940
Mitchell was a brilliant theoretician,

525
00:26:44,940 --> 00:26:46,740
he was cac-handed in the lab,

526
00:26:46,740 --> 00:26:48,340
he could never finish an experiment,

527
00:26:48,340 --> 00:26:50,940
it was Moyle that really did the experimental work,

528
00:26:50,940 --> 00:26:53,940
and Mitchell, of course, perhaps you don't know,

529
00:26:53,940 --> 00:26:59,220
but Mitchell in 1978 was awarded the Nobel Prize for chemistry by himself,

530
00:26:59,220 --> 00:27:00,900
I'm increasingly thinking,

531
00:27:00,900 --> 00:27:04,340
and I've been kind of digging around in the literature,

532
00:27:04,420 --> 00:27:07,580
but I think now, if that were to happen,

533
00:27:07,580 --> 00:27:09,540
then Moyle would have won the Nobel Prize with him,

534
00:27:09,540 --> 00:27:11,740
I think luckily times are changing,

535
00:27:11,740 --> 00:27:14,660
but I think that was a miscarriage of justice.

536
00:27:14,660 --> 00:27:19,540
Anyway, before this hypothesis was first published in 1961,

537
00:27:19,540 --> 00:27:23,100
Mitchell was a conference in Moscow, 1957,

538
00:27:23,100 --> 00:27:25,740
on the origin of life, it was organised by Oparin,

539
00:27:25,740 --> 00:27:31,220
who was a great Soviet, I suppose he was a chemist,

540
00:27:31,220 --> 00:27:33,060
interested in the origin of life,

541
00:27:33,060 --> 00:27:35,940
and a lot of the great scientists in the world at the time,

542
00:27:35,940 --> 00:27:38,500
so people like J.V.S. Haldane was there,

543
00:27:39,620 --> 00:27:43,460
and Mitchell himself was there as well,

544
00:27:43,460 --> 00:27:45,380
and J.D. Bernal was there,

545
00:27:45,380 --> 00:27:46,420
a lot of them were communists,

546
00:27:46,420 --> 00:27:49,780
which was why they went to Moscow and why they were interested,

547
00:27:49,780 --> 00:27:55,060
but it's also interesting that because there's such a materialistic basis

548
00:27:55,060 --> 00:27:57,740
to Marxism and communism,

549
00:27:57,740 --> 00:28:00,900
they were interested in questions like the origin of life

550
00:28:00,900 --> 00:28:02,740
in a way that many other people weren't at the time,

551
00:28:02,740 --> 00:28:05,700
so there's a reason why it was happening in Moscow.

552
00:28:06,900 --> 00:28:12,580
Mitchell really was not a communist really at all,

553
00:28:13,460 --> 00:28:15,500
in fact, he was from a very wealthy family,

554
00:28:15,500 --> 00:28:18,940
and he used to drive a silver Rolls Royce around Cambridge

555
00:28:18,940 --> 00:28:20,700
during the war time,

556
00:28:21,420 --> 00:28:24,980
and this is quite a poetic view here,

557
00:28:24,980 --> 00:28:28,140
I love this quote because it's eye-opening

558
00:28:28,140 --> 00:28:29,580
when you think about the origin of life,

559
00:28:29,580 --> 00:28:33,340
he says, I cannot consider the organism without its environment.

560
00:28:33,340 --> 00:28:34,300
From a formal point of view,

561
00:28:34,300 --> 00:28:37,420
the two may be regarded as equivalent phases

562
00:28:37,420 --> 00:28:39,580
between which dynamic contact is maintained

563
00:28:39,580 --> 00:28:42,180
by the membranes that separate and link them.

564
00:28:43,580 --> 00:28:47,900
So the inside of a cell in the outside world are equivalent phases.

565
00:28:47,900 --> 00:28:51,420
He's not separating life out and saying this is what life is

566
00:28:51,420 --> 00:28:52,620
and this is what the environment is,

567
00:28:52,620 --> 00:28:53,780
he's conflating them,

568
00:28:53,780 --> 00:28:56,460
he's saying they're equivalent to each other,

569
00:28:56,460 --> 00:28:57,940
which is a strange thing to say,

570
00:28:57,940 --> 00:28:59,300
but if you're thinking about the origin of life

571
00:28:59,300 --> 00:29:01,980
before there is such a thing as a cell that we would recognise,

572
00:29:01,980 --> 00:29:04,980
before there is really an organism or a living system,

573
00:29:04,980 --> 00:29:06,860
thinking about phases as your equivalent

574
00:29:06,860 --> 00:29:09,460
separated and joined by a membrane

575
00:29:09,460 --> 00:29:12,060
is a very productive way of thinking about the question.

576
00:29:13,700 --> 00:29:16,420
And this is, to my mind,

577
00:29:16,420 --> 00:29:18,780
what we have in a hydrothermal vent,

578
00:29:18,780 --> 00:29:20,460
we have a barrier,

579
00:29:20,460 --> 00:29:23,540
and we have alkaline hydrothermal fluids inside,

580
00:29:23,540 --> 00:29:26,060
and we have acidic ocean waters on the outside,

581
00:29:26,140 --> 00:29:28,940
and so the topology is equivalent to a bacterial cell.

582
00:29:28,940 --> 00:29:30,060
Here's a bacterial cell.

583
00:29:30,060 --> 00:29:32,300
We're pumping out protons,

584
00:29:32,300 --> 00:29:34,580
and so it's relatively acidic on the outside

585
00:29:34,580 --> 00:29:36,420
and it's relatively alkaline on the inside,

586
00:29:36,420 --> 00:29:39,860
and potentially it's three pH units difference

587
00:29:39,860 --> 00:29:41,220
between the inside and the outside.

588
00:29:41,220 --> 00:29:46,140
So it's the same magnitude and it's the same topology as a cell.

589
00:29:46,140 --> 00:29:49,980
So is there any way that we can kind of go from here to there?

590
00:29:49,980 --> 00:29:51,180
The other thing to notice about this,

591
00:29:51,180 --> 00:29:54,740
we're pumping out protons all the time in our own body,

592
00:29:54,740 --> 00:29:56,540
but why?

593
00:29:56,540 --> 00:29:59,620
Because we're putting them to work, to power work,

594
00:29:59,620 --> 00:30:02,100
and so the influx of protons is driving work,

595
00:30:02,100 --> 00:30:04,340
and the influx of protons across here

596
00:30:04,340 --> 00:30:06,540
could potentially drive work as well.

597
00:30:08,100 --> 00:30:10,060
What kind of work could it potentially do?

598
00:30:10,060 --> 00:30:13,380
Before there are any enzymes, any genes,

599
00:30:13,380 --> 00:30:16,180
any kind of structures that you would think

600
00:30:16,180 --> 00:30:18,300
could do anything useful,

601
00:30:18,300 --> 00:30:19,780
what on earth could it actually do?

602
00:30:19,780 --> 00:30:22,100
Well, there is a simple answer,

603
00:30:22,100 --> 00:30:25,660
and it's basically about driving growth.

604
00:30:25,660 --> 00:30:27,140
Why would that happen?

605
00:30:27,140 --> 00:30:29,260
The problem with hydrogen and CO2

606
00:30:29,260 --> 00:30:31,420
is they're just not very reactive.

607
00:30:31,420 --> 00:30:34,500
The first couple of steps to get them to react

608
00:30:34,500 --> 00:30:35,820
is really difficult,

609
00:30:35,820 --> 00:30:38,180
and so if you were to just take a mixture of gases,

610
00:30:38,180 --> 00:30:40,100
hydrogen and CO2, and put them in a test tube

611
00:30:40,100 --> 00:30:41,500
and heat them up to say 50 degrees

612
00:30:41,500 --> 00:30:43,620
and shake them up for half a billion years,

613
00:30:43,620 --> 00:30:46,100
nothing much is really going to happen.

614
00:30:46,100 --> 00:30:49,300
Actually, thermodynamically, you should get cells.

615
00:30:49,300 --> 00:30:50,660
Incredibly, you should get cells.

616
00:30:50,660 --> 00:30:53,100
They are more thermodynamically favored

617
00:30:53,100 --> 00:30:56,060
than just a mixture of hydrogen and CO2.

618
00:30:56,060 --> 00:30:58,500
The problem is this first couple of steps

619
00:30:58,500 --> 00:31:01,220
to get to formaldehyde is uphill.

620
00:31:01,220 --> 00:31:05,700
We don't need to go into the details of redox chemistry.

621
00:31:05,700 --> 00:31:07,860
All you really need to notice is it's uphill

622
00:31:07,860 --> 00:31:10,460
and it's quite steeply uphill to get them to react.

623
00:31:10,460 --> 00:31:13,260
But that is at the same pH.

624
00:31:13,260 --> 00:31:15,220
What we actually have in a hydrothermal vent

625
00:31:15,220 --> 00:31:17,860
is the alkaline fluids at pH 11

626
00:31:17,860 --> 00:31:21,700
and the acidic ocean waters, let's say pH 6.

627
00:31:21,700 --> 00:31:24,140
And now you can see it's downhill.

628
00:31:24,140 --> 00:31:25,700
Why is it downhill?

629
00:31:25,700 --> 00:31:28,660
It's quite simple, again, intuitively to understand.

630
00:31:28,660 --> 00:31:30,420
If you imagine hydrogen gas,

631
00:31:30,420 --> 00:31:33,060
it wants to pass its electrons onto something else.

632
00:31:33,060 --> 00:31:35,300
That leaves behind the protons,

633
00:31:35,300 --> 00:31:37,740
and the protons, well, that's what makes an acid.

634
00:31:37,740 --> 00:31:41,980
So an acid is rich in protons.

635
00:31:41,980 --> 00:31:44,860
If you make those protons in an alkaline environment,

636
00:31:44,860 --> 00:31:47,220
they'll immediately react with hydroxide to form water.

637
00:31:47,220 --> 00:31:48,620
It's a neutralisation reaction.

638
00:31:48,620 --> 00:31:51,820
It's extremely rapid, it's thermodynamically favoured.

639
00:31:51,820 --> 00:31:55,140
It's going to happen instantaneously and release a lot of heat.

640
00:31:55,140 --> 00:31:57,020
So it's just a neutralisation.

641
00:31:57,020 --> 00:31:59,700
If you try to release protons in an acidic environment,

642
00:31:59,700 --> 00:32:01,380
well, you're making an acid more acid,

643
00:32:01,380 --> 00:32:04,940
that's not really favoured in terms of chemistry.

644
00:32:04,940 --> 00:32:07,300
So it's going to be much more reactive

645
00:32:07,300 --> 00:32:08,740
in an alkaline environment.

646
00:32:08,740 --> 00:32:11,020
And CO2, well, it picks up an electron,

647
00:32:11,020 --> 00:32:12,460
now it's got a negative charge.

648
00:32:12,460 --> 00:32:13,860
If it's in an acidic environment,

649
00:32:13,860 --> 00:32:15,180
it can pick up a proton now.

650
00:32:15,180 --> 00:32:17,420
It's balanced the charges now, another electron now,

651
00:32:17,420 --> 00:32:19,900
another proton, and off we go, we can make it.

652
00:32:19,900 --> 00:32:22,140
So it becomes easier.

653
00:32:22,140 --> 00:32:25,820
CO2 becomes more reactive in an acidic environment.

654
00:32:25,820 --> 00:32:28,500
And so its downhill is going to happen

655
00:32:28,500 --> 00:32:32,900
so long as we have hydrogen in one phase at pH 11

656
00:32:32,900 --> 00:32:35,660
and CO2 in a different phase at pH 6,

657
00:32:35,660 --> 00:32:37,980
and they're not constantly mixing.

658
00:32:37,980 --> 00:32:41,140
They're not just forming the same thing.

659
00:32:41,140 --> 00:32:43,740
So that's what we have in these vents.

660
00:32:43,740 --> 00:32:45,380
And this is a fairly simple experiment.

661
00:32:45,380 --> 00:32:47,020
Actually, we've been building reactors

662
00:32:47,020 --> 00:32:49,180
and trying to make these things react for quite a long time

663
00:32:49,180 --> 00:32:50,780
and embarrassingly long time.

664
00:32:50,780 --> 00:32:52,060
And it's got smaller and smaller

665
00:32:52,060 --> 00:32:53,380
and more and more controllable.

666
00:32:53,380 --> 00:32:55,780
And this is a microfluidic chip.

667
00:32:55,780 --> 00:32:57,380
You can see it there as well.

668
00:32:57,380 --> 00:33:01,220
Inside this anaerobic glove box.

669
00:33:01,220 --> 00:33:07,420
And we have parallel flow, acidic flow with iron chloride

670
00:33:07,420 --> 00:33:09,380
and alkaline flow with sodium sulfide.

671
00:33:09,380 --> 00:33:12,460
And it precipitates this very thin barrier.

672
00:33:12,540 --> 00:33:15,220
And what we're hoping is that protons or maybe electrons

673
00:33:15,220 --> 00:33:18,060
when still not sure which, unbelievably,

674
00:33:18,060 --> 00:33:21,340
will cross this barrier and reduce CO2

675
00:33:21,340 --> 00:33:23,500
to make organic molecules.

676
00:33:23,500 --> 00:33:24,300
Does it work?

677
00:33:24,300 --> 00:33:25,260
Well, yes it does.

678
00:33:25,260 --> 00:33:29,620
It's not hugely impressive, I have to admit.

679
00:33:29,620 --> 00:33:31,620
It's taken a long time even to get to this.

680
00:33:31,620 --> 00:33:35,500
This is the kind of thing, if you're not a scientist,

681
00:33:35,500 --> 00:33:38,460
then maybe this will help you understand.

682
00:33:38,460 --> 00:33:42,140
People get amazingly excited about that.

683
00:33:42,140 --> 00:33:44,380
That is formate.

684
00:33:44,380 --> 00:33:47,020
Which is to say, it's the very first step

685
00:33:47,020 --> 00:33:48,740
of reacting hydrogen and CO2

686
00:33:48,740 --> 00:33:51,620
to make the very first product.

687
00:33:51,620 --> 00:33:53,780
So it's a step in the right direction.

688
00:33:53,780 --> 00:33:56,620
And it's sticking up quite a long way above this baseline.

689
00:33:56,620 --> 00:33:59,300
Sometimes this baseline is quite lumpy and bumpy

690
00:33:59,300 --> 00:34:01,980
and so this is not a bad peak really.

691
00:34:01,980 --> 00:34:06,580
And so it's proof that it can begin to happen.

692
00:34:06,580 --> 00:34:12,660
And over here, this one is acetate,

693
00:34:12,660 --> 00:34:14,700
which is two carbons joined together.

694
00:34:14,700 --> 00:34:16,540
And we've managed to get three carbons joined together

695
00:34:16,540 --> 00:34:20,220
and you'll probably be thinking, wow, well done.

696
00:34:20,220 --> 00:34:24,420
But it's taken us 10 years.

697
00:34:24,420 --> 00:34:26,940
It's a bit embarrassing, as I say.

698
00:34:26,940 --> 00:34:29,700
Other people have gone much further

699
00:34:29,700 --> 00:34:31,860
but they've very often used higher pressures

700
00:34:31,860 --> 00:34:34,220
and all kinds of interesting minerals.

701
00:34:34,220 --> 00:34:36,180
This is with very freshly precipitated

702
00:34:36,180 --> 00:34:37,300
with just a pH gradient.

703
00:34:37,300 --> 00:34:39,380
And if you cut out the pH gradient,

704
00:34:39,380 --> 00:34:41,140
it doesn't work, you don't get anything.

705
00:34:41,140 --> 00:34:43,580
If you cut out some of the transition metals like nickel,

706
00:34:43,580 --> 00:34:44,940
it doesn't work, you don't get anything.

707
00:34:44,940 --> 00:34:49,340
So even though it looks incredibly cheap,

708
00:34:49,340 --> 00:34:51,380
it is actually quite exciting.

709
00:34:51,380 --> 00:34:54,420
It's a proof of concept that a pH gradient across a barrier

710
00:34:54,420 --> 00:34:58,540
will drive CO2 fixation and make the organic molecules.

711
00:34:58,540 --> 00:35:01,580
And notice acetate, it's actually one of the Krebs cycle.

712
00:35:01,580 --> 00:35:03,900
And the reverse Krebs cycle is one of the intermediates,

713
00:35:03,900 --> 00:35:08,420
one of the universally conserved intermediates.

714
00:35:08,420 --> 00:35:11,340
Now, I said other people have done more than we have.

715
00:35:11,340 --> 00:35:13,140
We're now talking higher temperatures

716
00:35:13,140 --> 00:35:14,780
and higher pressures and things like that.

717
00:35:14,780 --> 00:35:18,980
But some people have produced longer chain fatty acids

718
00:35:18,980 --> 00:35:21,100
doing that.

719
00:35:21,100 --> 00:35:24,260
And they'd done that 20 years ago, actually,

720
00:35:24,260 --> 00:35:25,980
not using pH gradients.

721
00:35:25,980 --> 00:35:29,140
And we'd taken a selection of these and tried to see,

722
00:35:29,140 --> 00:35:31,700
well, if you remember my picture,

723
00:35:31,700 --> 00:35:37,700
I was showing you a proto cell nestling snugly inside a pore.

724
00:35:37,700 --> 00:35:39,340
Well, that requires a bilayer membrane,

725
00:35:39,340 --> 00:35:41,180
and that requires something really simple.

726
00:35:41,180 --> 00:35:43,700
And so the question is, if we take these fatty acids that

727
00:35:43,700 --> 00:35:46,820
have been made and something called fatty alcohols, which

728
00:35:46,820 --> 00:35:49,540
also is kind of a long chain of covens joined together

729
00:35:49,540 --> 00:35:52,060
with an alcohol group stuck on the end,

730
00:35:52,060 --> 00:35:53,740
do we get things that look like proto cells?

731
00:35:53,740 --> 00:35:56,980
And the answer is yes, this is cryoelectron microscopy,

732
00:35:56,980 --> 00:35:59,820
and it's got a bilayer membrane around an aqueous space

733
00:35:59,820 --> 00:36:01,420
inside these similar things.

734
00:36:01,420 --> 00:36:07,460
This is confocal microscopy, and I think this one is at pH 7,

735
00:36:07,460 --> 00:36:10,540
but this one's at pH 12, and these are also at pH 12.

736
00:36:10,540 --> 00:36:13,780
So we are able to make them, and they

737
00:36:13,780 --> 00:36:17,780
make stable proto cells quite beautiful to look at.

738
00:36:17,780 --> 00:36:19,820
When you see them live, as it were,

739
00:36:19,820 --> 00:36:22,020
they're moving around and doing interesting things.

740
00:36:22,020 --> 00:36:24,580
They're quite dynamic.

741
00:36:24,580 --> 00:36:28,660
So yes, and the question there was, well,

742
00:36:28,660 --> 00:36:31,940
are they stable in these harsh conditions in a hydrothermal vent

743
00:36:31,940 --> 00:36:36,420
at 70 degrees centigrade and pH 9 or 10 or 11,

744
00:36:36,420 --> 00:36:40,900
and lots of salt and calcium and magnesium and all the rest of it?

745
00:36:40,900 --> 00:36:43,420
And the answer is yes, that has all of those things in.

746
00:36:43,420 --> 00:36:48,940
So it is quite easy to make them, it turns out.

747
00:36:48,940 --> 00:36:52,300
And this, I'm not going to go through the details here,

748
00:36:52,300 --> 00:36:56,060
but this is another thing where scientists get ridiculously

749
00:36:56,060 --> 00:37:00,980
excited about, let's say, that, this little shoulder here.

750
00:37:00,980 --> 00:37:03,820
This is what's called UV-viz spectroscopy,

751
00:37:03,820 --> 00:37:08,860
and that shoulder is diagnostic of what are called 4FE4S clusters,

752
00:37:08,860 --> 00:37:12,860
which is a kind of little cube of iron and sulfur.

753
00:37:12,860 --> 00:37:15,020
And they're found in some of the most important proteins

754
00:37:15,020 --> 00:37:17,300
in biology, things like ferrodoxin, which

755
00:37:17,300 --> 00:37:21,740
are directly doing CO2 fixation in pretty much all cells.

756
00:37:21,740 --> 00:37:25,140
These are ancient proteins, and they always contain these little cubes

757
00:37:25,140 --> 00:37:29,020
of iron and sulfur, and they're like minerals.

